04612nam a22005295i 9780674270091DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742700917 a10.4159/97806742700912doi  a(DE-B1597)600600  a(OCoLC)1280945214  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHG1710.3b.P73 2021 7aBUS0450002bisacsh04a332.4223  aQK 2002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/141634:1 aPrasad, Eswar S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Future of Money :bHow the Digital Revolution Is Transforming Currencies and Finance /cEswar S. Prasad. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (446 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPART I. Laying the Bedrock -- tCHAPTER 1. Racing to the Future -- tCHAPTER 2. Money and Finance -- tPART II. Innovations -- tCHAPTER 3. Will Fintech Make the World a Better Place? -- tCHAPTER 4. Bitcoin Sets Off a Revolution, Then Falters -- tCHAPTER 5. Crypto Mania -- tPART III. Central Bank -- tCHAPTER 6. The Case for Central Bank Digital Currencies -- tCHAPTER 7. Getting Central Bank Digital Currencies Off the Ground -- tPART IV. Ramifications -- tCHAPTER 8. Consequences for the International Monetary System -- tCHAPTER 9. Central Banks Run the Gauntlet -- tCHAPTER 10. A Glorious Future Beckons, Perhaps -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA cutting-edge look at how accelerating financial change, from the end of cash to the rise of cryptocurrencies, will transform economies for better and worse. We think we’ve seen financial innovation. We bank from laptops and buy coffee with the wave of a phone. But these are minor miracles compared with the dizzying experiments now underway around the globe, as businesses and governments alike embrace the possibilities of new financial technologies. As Eswar Prasad explains, the world of finance is at the threshold of major disruption that will affect corporations, bankers, states, and indeed all of us. The transformation of money will fundamentally rewrite how ordinary people live. Above all, Prasad foresees the end of physical cash. The driving force won’t be phones or credit cards but rather central banks, spurred by the emergence of cryptocurrencies to develop their own, more stable digital currencies. Meanwhile, cryptocurrencies themselves will evolve unpredictably as global corporations like Facebook and Amazon join the game. The changes will be accompanied by snowballing innovations that are reshaping finance and have already begun to revolutionize how we invest, trade, insure, and manage risk. Prasad shows how these and other changes will redefine the very concept of money, unbundling its traditional functions as a unit of account, medium of exchange, and store of value. The promise lies in greater efficiency and flexibility, increased sensitivity to the needs of diverse consumers, and improved market access for the unbanked. The risk is instability, lack of accountability, and erosion of privacy. A lucid, visionary work, The Future of Money shows how to maximize the best and guard against the worst of what is to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBanks and banking, Central. 0aDigital currency. 0aInternational finance. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Money & Monetary Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067427009140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674270091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674270091/original  a978-